-- BNP Paribas, Bureau Veritas, Casino, France Telecom: French Equity Preview
-- Adria Cimino
-- 2010-06-22T06:22:19Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-22/bnp-paribas-bureau-veritas-casino-france-telecom-french-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following is a list of companies
whose stocks may be active in Paris. Symbols are in parentheses
after company names and prices are from the last close.  
 July futures on France’s CAC 40 Index lost 35.5 to 3,695.5
at 8:08 a.m. in Paris.  
 The CAC 40 rose 1.3 percent to 3,736.15 points yesterday.
The SBF 120 Index advanced 1.2 percent.  
 Air France-KLM Group SA  (AF FP): JPMorgan Chase & Co.
raised its recommendation on shares of Europe’s biggest airline
to “overweight” from “underweight.” The stock climbed 0.5
percent to 11.13 euros.  
 BNP Paribas SA  (BNP FP): Fitch Ratings cut the credit
rating for France’s largest bank one step to AA-, the fourth-
highest investment grade, citing a “deterioration” of the
company’s asset quality. The outlook is stable, Fitch said. The
shares rose 0.3 percent to 50.32 euros.  
 Bouygues SA  (EN FP): The company won a contract worth 273
million euros ($336 million) to renovate the Velodrome stadium
in Marseille, Le Figaro reported, citing Marseille mayor Claude
Gaudin. The stock increased 0.1 percent to 35.40 euros.  
 Bureau Veritas SA  (BVI FP): The company agreed to buy
Inspectorate from 3i Group Plc for 450 million pounds to become
one of the three largest commodity-testing businesses. The
operation will add to earnings per share from the first year,
Chief Executive Officer  Frank Piedelievre  said. The stock rose
0.5 percent to 45.30 euros.  
 Casino Guichard-Perrachon SA  (CO FP): The biggest Paris
supermarket owner raised its stake in Brazil’s Cia. Brasileira
de Distribuicao Grupo Pao de Acucar to 33.7 percent from 33.4
percent previously through the purchase of 1.1 million
preference shares for 30 million euros. The shares were
unchanged at 65.25 euros.  
 Electricite de France SA  (EDF FP): Europe’s biggest power
generator said a law under debate in France’s Senate may force
the company to sell power to rivals at prices that would leave
profit from the sales at zero. The stock gained 0.8 percent to
36.06 euros.  
 France Telecom SA  (FTE FP): France’s largest telephone
company is part of a group of companies offering about 100
million euros for control of French newspaper Le Monde,
according to a person familiar with the situation. France
Telecom shares fell 0.7 percent to 15.30 euros.  
 Ipsen SA  (IPN FP): The company said its Guidage treatment
did not meet its primary objective in preventing Alzheimer
dementia in the whole test population. The stock lost 2.7
percent to 26.35 euros.  
